        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our proposed decisive detection of the QPOs of Sgr A* strongly depends on the atmospheric conditions, then it is important to observe with clear and stable weather condition for Band 7. However, we expect the chance of achieving such conditions are relatively high for Band 7 at the ALMA site.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We require to observe Sgr A with continuous observing span of 5 hours (or as long as technically possible) and a successive observation of Sgr A without any switching both in observing frequency and in observing target. We have to observe band-pass calibrator before or after full track and to carry out pointing/atmosphere calibrations also. Around Sgr A*, there are the extended bright components of the HII region called mini-spiral. To filter out the emission from these components, we need to angular resolution better than 1" in band 7. So we require configurations which archive such angular resolution. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The flux density of Sgr A* is expected to be brighter than 3.0 Jy in Band 7, and the S/N of the QPO amplitudes (0.5 % of the flux density) is required to be much larger than 15 mJy. 
Because the QPO amplitudes themselves are expected to be smaller than the apparent flux density variation of SgrA* at 340 GHz. It is necessary to set correlator bandwidth to its maximum of 7.5 GHz and to observe dual polarization to get high sensitivity. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We calibrate visibility data with self-calibration. Sgr A* is probably strong enough to improve calibration accuracy using self-calibration. After calibrating the whole time data, we make a series of snap shot maps from the same calibrations, and we measure the flux density of Sgr A* from the snap shot maps. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ADDITIONAL_TIME</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
